      = [[List of million-plus agglomerations in India|21st]]\n| population_demonym              = Bhopali\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|Pincode]]\n| postal_code                     = 462001 to 462050\n| area_code                       = 0755\n| area_code_type                  = [[Communications in India|Telephone]]\n| registration_plate              = MP-04\n| website                         = {{URL|http://www.bhopal.nic.in}} , {{URL|http://www.smartbhopal.city/}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| leader_title3                   = [[Member of Parliament]]\n| leader_name3                    = [[Pragya Singh Thakur]] (2019 \u2013 present)\n| blank2_name_sec1                = [[Precipitation (meteorology)|Precipitation]]\n| blank2_info_sec1                = {{convert|1,123.1|mm|in}}\n| blank3_name_sec1                = [[Official language]]\n| blank3_info_sec1                = [[Hindi]]\n| blank4_name_sec1                = Avg. high temperature\n| blank4_info_sec1                = {{convert|31.7|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}\n| blank5_name_sec1                = Avg. low temperature\n| blank5_info_sec1                = {{convert|18.6|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}\n}}\n'''Bhopal''' ({{IPAc-en|b|o\u028a|\u02c8|p|\u0251\u02d0|l}}; {{IPA-hns|b\u02b1o\u02d0pa\u02d0l|-|Bhopal.ogg}}) is the [[capital (political)|capital]] city of the [[Indian state]] of [[Madhya Pradesh]] and the administrative headquarters of both [[Bhopal district]] and [[Bhopal division]]. Bhopal is known as ''The City of Lakes''<ref name=\"BritannicaEducational2010\">{{cite book|author=Educational Britannica Educational|title=The Geography of India: Sacred and Historic Places|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xPUvqtdfjyAC&pg=PA174|accessdate=15 April 2012|date=1 July 2010|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-61530-202-4|pages=174\u2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523040334/http://books.google.com/books?id=xPUvqtdfjyAC&pg=PA174|archive-date=23 May 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> for its various natural and artificial lakes and is also one of the greenest cities in India.<ref>{{cite web|author=Green |url=http://green.in.msn.com/greenliving/article.aspx?cp-documentid=3490719&page=7 |title=MSN's 8 green cities of India \u2013 7 \u2013 Green News \u2013 Article \u2013 MSN India |publisher=Green.in.msn.com |date=28 January 2010 |accessdate=26 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091228002937/http://green.in.msn.com/greenliving/article.aspx?cp-documentid=3490719&page=7 |archivedate=28 December 2009 }}</ref> It is the [[List of cities in India by population#1 to 50|16th largest city]] in India and 131st<ref name=\"Estimated Population of Bhopal urban area in 2009, Bhopal 131th largest city in world in 2009/\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldatlas.com/citypops.htm|title=The world's largest cities|publisher=City Mayors|accessdate=16 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828095658/http://www.worldatlas.com/citypops.htm|archive-date=28 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> in the world.\n\nFounded in 1707, the city was the capital of the former [[Bhopal State]], a [[princely state]] of the British ruled by the [[Nawabs of Bhopal]]. Numerous heritage structures from this period include the [[Taj-ul-Masajid]] and [[Taj Mahal (palace)|Taj Mahal palace]]. In 1984, the city was struck by the [[Bhopal disaster]], one of the worst industrial disasters in history.\n\nA [[Classification of Indian cities|Y-class city]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Re-classification/Upgradation of Cities/Towns on the basis of Census-2011 for the purpose of grant of House Rent Allowance (HRA) to Central Government Employees|url=https://www.finmin.nic.in/sites/default/files/21-07-2015_0.pdf|publisher=Ministry of Finance \u2013 Government of India|accessdate=14 June 2018|date=21 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118061832/http://www.finmin.nic.in/sites/default/files/21-07-2015_0.pdf|archive-date=18 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Bhopal houses various educational and research institutions and installations of national importance, including [[ISRO]]'s [[INSAT Master Control Facility|Master Control Facility]],<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.isro.org/newsletters/spaceindia/oct2004jun2005/Chapter2.htm\n| title = ISRO Master Control Facility\n| accessdate = 27 March 2007\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930153945/http://www.isro.org/newsletters/spaceindia/oct2004jun2005/Chapter2.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 30 September 2007 }}</ref> [[Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited|BHEL]], and [[Advanced Materials and Processes Research Institute|AMPRI]]. Bhopal is home to the largest number of [[List of Institutes of National Importance|institutes of National Importance]] in India, namely [[Indian Institute of Science Education and Research, Bhopal|IISER]], [[Maulana Azad National Institute of Technology Bhopal|MANIT]], [[School of Planning and Architecture, Bhopal|SPA]], [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences Bhopal|AIIMS]], [[National Law Institute University|NLIU]], [[Indian Institute of Forest Management|IIFM]] and [[Indian Institute of Information Technology, Bhopal|IIIT]] (currently functioning from a temporary campus inside [[Maulana Azad National Institute of Technology|MANIT]]) .\n\nThe city attracted international attention in December 1984 after the [[Bhopal disaster]], when a [[Union Carbide India Limited]] (UCIL) pesticide manufacturing plant (now owned by [[Dow Chemical Company]]) leaked a mixture of deadly gases composed mainly of [[methyl isocyanate]], leading to one of the worst industrial disasters in the world's history. The Bhopal disaster continues to be a part of the socio-political debate and a logistical challenge for the people of Bhopal.<ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\">[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhopal/Government-braces-for-disposal-of-Carbide-waste-at-Pithampur/articleshow/35422050.cms Government braces for disposal of Carbide waste at Pithampur] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140526140723/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhopal/Government-braces-for-disposal-of-Carbide-waste-at-Pithampur/articleshow/35422050.cms |date=26 May 2014 }} The Times of India, 21 May 2014</ref>\n\nBhopal was selected as one of the first twenty Indian cities (the first phase) to be developed as a [[Smart City Bhopal|smart city]] under [[Narendra Modi|PM Narendra Modi's]] flagship [[Smart Cities Mission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/business/why-only-98-cities-instead-of-100-announced-all-questions-answered-about-smart-cities-project-2410576.html|title=Why only 98 cities instead of 100 announced: All questions answered about smart cities project|date=28 August 2015|accessdate=25 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119003746/http://www.firstpost.com/business/why-only-98-cities-instead-of-100-announced-all-questions-answered-about-smart-cities-project-2410576.html|archive-date=19 January 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Bhopal has also been rated as the cleanest capital city for three consecutive years, 2017, 2018 and 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ayub |first1=Jamal |title=Swachh Survekshan 2019: Indore cleanest city, Bhopal cleanest capital {{!}} Bhopal News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhopal/swachh-survekshan-2019-indore-cleanest-city-bhopal-cleanest-capital/articleshow/68283117.cms |accessdate=21 January 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=6 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early history ===\n[[File:Statue of Raja Bhoja 01.jpg|thumb|  Bhopal was founded by and named after 11th century [[Malwa]] king [[Bhoja]]]]\nAccording to folklore, Bhopal was founded in the 11th century by the [[Paramara dynasty|Paramara]] king [[Bhoja]], who ruled from his capital at [[Dhar]]. This theory states that Bhopal was originally known as Bhojpal after a dam (''pal'') constructed by the king's minister.<ref name=census /> No archaeological evidence, inscriptions or historical texts support the claim about an earlier settlement founded by Bhoja at the same place. An alternative theory says that the city is named after another king called Bhupala (or Bhupal).<ref>{{cite book | title = Historical Geography of Madhya Pradesh from Early Records | author = Pranab Kumar Bhattacharyya | publisher = [[Motilal Banarsidass]] | year = 1977 | isbn = 978-0-8426-9091-1 | page = 275 }}</ref><ref>[http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/MP-BHO-cpi-joins-campaign-against-naming-bhopal-as-bhojpal-1939473.html CPI joins campaign against naming Bhopal as Bhojpal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123014730/http://daily.bhaskar.com/article/MP-BHO-cpi-joins-campaign-against-naming-bhopal-as-bhojpal-1939473.html |date=23 November 2011 }}. Daily Bhaskar,16 March 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Ashfaq Ali |title=Bhopal, Past and Present |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=owMMAQAAIAAJ |year=1981 |publisher=Jai Bharat |page=xxix |access-date=19 February 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223154011/https://books.google.com/books?id=owMMAQAAIAAJ |archive-date=23 December 2016 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n[[File:Mausoleum of Dost Khan Bhopal.jpg|thumb|Mausoleum of Dost Khan founder of Bhopal state]]\nIn the early 18th century, Bhopal was a small village in the [[Gondi people|Gond]] kingdom. The modern Bhopal city was established by [[Dost Mohammad Khan, Nawab of Bhopal|Dost Mohammad Khan]] (1672\u20131728), a [[Pashtun people|Pashtun]] soldier in the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] army.<ref>{{cite book | title = The Waterhouse albums: central Indian provinces | author = John Falconer, James Waterhouse | publisher = Mapin | year = 2009 | isbn = 978-81-89995-30-0 }}</ref> After the death of the emperor [[Aurangzeb]], Khan started providing mercenary services to local chieftains in the politically unstable [[Malwa]] region. In 1709, he took on the lease of [[Berasia]] estate and later annexed several territories in the region to establish the [[Bhopal State]].{{sfn|Khan|2000|p=11}} Khan received the territory of Bhopal from the Gond queen Kamlapati in lieu of payment for mercenary services and usurped her kingdom after her death.<ref name=\"KamlaMittal_1990\">{{cite book | title = History of Bhopal State | author = Kamla Mittal | publisher = Munshiram Manoharlal | year = 1990 | oclc = 551527788 | page = 2 }}</ref> In the 1720s, he built the Fatehgarh fort in the village, which developed into the city of Bhopal over the next few decades.\n\n=== Begum rule ===\nBhopal became a [[princely state]] after signing a treaty with the [[British East India Company]] in 1818.{{sfn|Khan|2000|p=68}} Between 1819 and 1926, the state was ruled by four women, [[Begum of Bhopal|Begums]] \u2014 unique in the royalty of those days \u2014 under British suzerainty. [[Qudsia Begum of Bhopal|Qudsia Begum]] was the first woman ruler (between 1819\u20131837), who was succeeded by her granddaughter, [[Sultan Shah Jahan, Begum of Bhopal|Shah Jehan]]. Between the years 1844\u20131860, when Shah Jehan was a child, her mother [[Nawab Sikandar, Begum of Bhopal|Sikandar]] (only daughter of Qudsia) ruled as regent, and was then recognised as ruler in 1860. She ruled until 1868, when Shah Jehan succeeded her and was Begum until 1901. In 1901, Shah Jehan's daughter [[Kaikhusrau Jahan, Begum of Bhopal|Kaikhusrau Jahan]] became Begum, ruled until 1926, and was the last of the female line of succession. In 1926, she abdicated in favour of her son, [[Hamidullah Khan]], who ruled until 1947, and was the last of the sovereign [[Nawab]]s. The rule of Begums gave the city its waterworks, railways, a postal system, and a municipality constituted in 1907.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bhopalmunicipal.com/history.htm |title=BMC History |accessdate=12 June 2007 |date=15 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070412043526/http://bhopalmunicipal.com/history.htm |archivedate=12 April 2007  }}</ref>\n\n=== Post independence ===\n[[Bhopal State]] was the second-largest Muslim-ruled princely state: the first being [[Hyderabad State|Hyderabad]]. After the [[independence of India]] in 1947, the last Nawab expressed his wish to retain Bhopal as a separate unit. Agitations against the Nawab broke out in December 1948, leading to the arrest of prominent leaders including [[Shankar Dayal Sharma]]. Later, the political detainees were released, and the Nawab signed the agreement for Bhopal's merger with the Union of India on 30 April 1949.<ref name=\"SRBakshi_OPRalhan_2007\">{{cite book | title = Madhya Pradesh Through the Ages | author = S.R. Bakshi and O.P. Ralhan | publisher = Sarup & Sons | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-81-7625-806-7 | page = 360 }}</ref> The [[Bhopal State (1949\u201356)|Bhopal state]] was taken over by the Union Government of India on 1 June 1949.\n\n=== Bhopal disaster ===\n{{Main|Bhopal disaster}}\nIn early December 1984, a [[Union Carbide India Limited]] pesticide plant in Bhopal leaked around 32 tons of toxic gases, including [[methyl isocyanate]] (MIC) gas which led to [[List of industrial disasters|the worst industrial disaster in the world to date]].\n\nThe official [[death toll]] was initially recorded as around 4,000. A Madhya Pradesh government report stated 3,787 deaths, while other estimates state the fatalities were significantly higher (16,000) from the accident and the medical complications caused by the accident in the weeks and years that followed. The higher estimates have been challenged.<ref name=\"Eckerman2005\">{{cite book |last=Eckerman |first=Ingrid |title=The Bhopal Saga\u2014Causes and Consequences of the World's Largest Industrial Disaster |url=http://eckerman.nu/the-bhopal-saga |year=2005 |publisher=Universities Press |location=India |isbn=81-7371-515-7 |access-date=16 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904023428/http://eckerman.nu/the-bhopal-saga |archive-date=4 September 2014 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>Carol Wood, [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1257585/ The Bhopal Saga: Causes and Consequences of the World\u2019s Largest Industrial Disaster] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917004424/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1257585/ |date=17 September 2018 }}, Environ Health Perspect., May 2005; 113(5): A344</ref> The impact of the disaster continues to this day in terms of psychological and neurological disabilities, blindness, skin, vision, breathing, and birth disorders.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1945229,00.html |title=Victims of Bhopal Mark Anniversary |author=ALTAF QADRI |date=3 December 2009 |work=Time |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609082241/http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0%2C8599%2C1945229%2C00.html |archivedate=9 June 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/bhopal-the-victims-are-still-being-born-1830516.html| title = Bhopal: The victims are still being born| work = [[The Independent]]| date = 29 November 2009| first = Nina| last = Lakhani| accessdate = 30 November 2009| location = London| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091203010047/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/bhopal-the-victims-are-still-being-born-1830516.html| archivedate= 3 December 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8392206.stm| title = Bhopal marks 25 years since gas leak devastation| work = BBC News| date = 3 December 2009| accessdate = 26 April 2010\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100607190104/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8392206.stm| archivedate= 7 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe soil and ground water near the factory site have been contaminated by the toxic wastes.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\" /><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.downtoearth.org.in/cover.asp?foldername=20091215&filename=news&sid=22&sec_id=9| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100418131307/http://downtoearth.org.in/cover.asp?foldername=20091215&filename=news&sid=22&sec_id=9| archivedate = 18 April 2010| title = Subterranean Leak}}</ref> The Bhopal disaster continues to be the part of the socio-political debate; the clean-up of environmental contamination and rehabilitation of those affected continues to challenge the people of Bhopal.<ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\" />\n\nComensation to families of the victims - The Centre is seeking a direction to [[Union Carbide]] and other firms for Rs 7,844 crore additional amount over and above the earlier settlement amount of USD 470 million in 1989 for paying compensation to the gas tragedy victims <ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/bhopal-gas-tragedy-sc-to-hear-centres-plea-for-additional-rs-7844-cr-fund-to-compensate-victims/amp_articleshow/73667264.cms |title= Bhopal gas tragedy: SC to hear Centre's plea for additional Rs 7,844 crore fund to compensate victims |date= 27 January 2020|publisher = [[Economic Times]] }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Bhojtal Upper Lake Bada Talaab and the city of Bhopal Madhya Pradesh India 2011.jpg|thumb|left|A view of upper lake, part of the city and the hilly [[Vindhya Range|Vindhya]] terrain.]]\nBhopal has an average elevation of 500&nbsp;metres (1401&nbsp;ft) and is located in the central part of India, just north of the upper limit of the [[Vindhya]] mountain ranges. Located on the [[Malwa]] plateau, it is higher than the north Indian plains and the land rises towards the [[Vindhya Range]] to the south. The city has uneven elevation and has small hills within its boundaries. The prominent hills in Bhopal are the Idgah and Shyamala hills in the northern region, together with the Katara hills in the southern region. There are two lakes namely [[Bhojtal|upper lake]] and [[Lower Lake, Bhopal|lower lake]]. The Upper Lake has a surface area of 36 km<sup>2</sup> and catchment area of 361 km<sup>2</sup> while the Lower Lake has a surface area of 1.29 km<sup>2</sup> and catchment area of 9.6 km<sup>2</sup><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jica.go.jp/english/our_work/evaluation/oda_loan/post/2007/pdf/project32_full.pdf|title=Lake Bhopal Conservation and Management Project|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. Recently, Bhopal Municipal Corporation came with a resolution to involve local citizens in cleaning, conserving and maintaining the lakes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/bhopal/bhopal-in-2020-bmc-resolves-to-work-on-parks-conservation-of-lakes-public-participation|title=Bhopal: In 2020 BMC resolves to work on parks, conservation of lakes & public participation|website=Free Press Journal|language=en|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> Bhopal city is divided into two parts where one part which is near the VIP and lake is Old Bhopal (north) and the other, New Bhopal (south), where  malls are mainly situated.\n{{climate chart\n| Bhopal\n| 9.4|24.4|12.9\n| 11.4|28.3|7.8\n| 17.1|33.6|7.2\n| 21.8|38.3|4.5\n| 25.5|40.7|8.0\n| 25.3|37.0|114.0\n| 23.1|30.6|355.8\n| 22.4|28.8|388.4\n| 21.4|30.5|195.8\n| 18.4|32.0|26.2\n| 12.1|29.0|13.7\n| 9.9|25.3|12.4\n| float=right\n| clear=right\n}}\n\n===Climate===\nBhopal has a [[humid subtropical climate]], with cool, dry winters, a hot summer and a humid monsoon season. Summers start in late March and go on till mid-June, the average temperature being around 30&nbsp;\u00b0C (86&nbsp;\u00b0F), with the peak of summer in May, when the highs regularly exceed 40&nbsp;\u00b0C (104&nbsp;\u00b0F) Extreme high in May was 46.7&nbsp;\u00b0C on 19 May 2016 and in June it was 45.9&nbsp;\u00b0C on 7 June 2019. The monsoon starts in late June and ends in late September. These months see about 40&nbsp;inches (1020&nbsp;mm) of precipitation, frequent thunderstorms and flooding. The average temperature is around 25&nbsp;\u00b0C (77&nbsp;\u00b0F) and the humidity is quite high. Temperatures rise again up to early November when winter starts, which lasts up to early March. Winters in Bhopal are cool, and not very much comfortable like summers, with average daily temperatures around 16&nbsp;\u00b0C (61&nbsp;\u00b0F). The winter peaks in January when temperatures may drop close to freezing on some nights. Lowest temperature ever recorded was 0.3&nbsp;\u00b0C. Total annual rainfall is about 1146&nbsp;mm (46&nbsp;inches).\n{{Bhopal weatherbox}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{bar box\n|title=Religion in Bhopal<ref name=\"icssr.org\">[http://www.icssr.org/Baseline%20Survey%20of%20Bhopal%20District.pdf Baseline Survey of Bhopal District, Madhya Pradesh] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130903030135/http://www.icssr.org/Baseline%20Survey%20of%20Bhopal%20District.pdf |date=3 September 2013 }} Ministry of Minority Affairs, Government of India (2012)</ref>\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|69.20}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|26.28}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jainism|Jains]]|pink|1.35}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|#5218FA|1.12}}\n{{bar percent|[[Buddhists]]|indigo|1.08}}\n{{bar percent|Others\u2020|black|0.6}}\n|caption=Population % by religion; \u2020<small>Includes [[Sikh]]s</small>\n}}\n\nAccording to the 2011 census, the population of the Bhopal city (the area under Bhopal Municipal Corporation) is 1,798,218, with 936,168 males and 862,050 females. The population of the Bhopal metropolitan area (the [[urban agglomeration]] that extends beyond Bhopal city) was 1,886,100 in 2011.<ref name=\"census_metro\">{{cite web |url=censusmp.nic.in/censusmp/All-PDF/Urban-data.ppt |title=Presentation on Towns and Urban Agglomerations |work=Census of India 2011 |accessdate=13 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314015213/http://censusmp.nic.in/censusmp/All-PDF/Workshop%20at%20Admn.Academy%20-%2013%20Nov.%202014/04.%20Urban-data.ppt |archivedate=14 March 2016  }}</ref> The total effective literacy rate (for population aged 7+ years) was 85.24%, with male and female literacy respectively at 89.2% and 80.1%.<ref name=census />[[File:Tourist Map of Bhopal.jpg|thumb|Tourist Map of Bhopal]]\n[[File:Bhopal pride Queermitra 04.jpg|thumb|157x157px|Bhopal Pride March]]\n[[File:Royal tiger 01.jpg|thumb|[[Tiger]] at [[Van Vihar National Park]]]]\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Bharat Bhavan Bhopal.JPG|thumb|Bharat Bhavan Bhopal]]\n[[Diwali]] and [[Eid ul-Fitr|Eid]] are major festivals in Bhopal. Gifts and sweets are exchanged and donation are made to the poor. Diwali is celebrated by worshiping the wealth goddess ''[[Lakshmi]]''. Eid is special to the city as all the Hindus take time out to visit their Muslim friends and greet them and get treated with delicacies, the speciality of the day being sweet ''sewaiya''. Bhopali culture is such that both Hindus and Muslims visit each other on their respective festivals to greet and exchange sweets. During [[Ganesh]] puja and [[Durga Puja]] (Navratras), idols of Ganesh and Durga are established in ''jhankis'' throughout the city. People throng to offer prayers to their deities. At the end of Navratras, on the day of [[Vijayadashami]] (or ''Dussehra''), huge effigies of [[Ravan]] are burnt in different parts of the city.\n\n[[Bhopal Ijtema]] is an annual Muslim world preachers congregation, is held at Ghasipura 11&nbsp;km from Bhopal. The annual congregation near Bhopal attracts between 500,000 and 1,000,000 Muslims globally.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bhopal|first=Ijtema|title=Ijtema|url=http://www.siasat.com/english/news/3-day-\u2018aalami-tablighi-ijtima\u2019-begin-bhopal-dec-14|access-date=21 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111192659/http://www.siasat.com/english/news/3-day-%E2%80%98aalami-tablighi-ijtima%E2%80%99-begin-bhopal-dec-14|archive-date=11 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe city was the first in state and all of central India to organise an LGBTQ+ pride march, the [[Bhopal Pride March]] on 17 May 2017 ([[International Day Against Homophobia, Transphobia and Biphobia]]). The march saw a huge participation from the members of the queer community as well as straight allies. It was followed in 2018 by a second edition which was held on 15 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/latest-news/bhopal-lgbtqs-pride-parade-from-july-1-to-15/1306736|title=Bhopal: LGBTQ's Pride Parade from July 1 to 15|publisher=Freepressjournal|access-date=2 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719080520/http://www.freepressjournal.in/latest-news/bhopal-lgbtqs-pride-parade-from-july-1-to-15/1306736|archive-date=19 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Architecture===\nThe [[Nawabs of Bhopal]] built several structures including the [[Taj-ul-Masajid]] and [[Taj Mahal (palace)|Taj Mahal palace]] in [[Indo-Islamic architecture|Indo-Islamic]] and European styles.\n\n[[Bharat Bhavan]] is the main cultural centre of the city, and hosts many theatre and film festivals every year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/bhopal/film-fest-ekagra-begins-at-bhara-bhavan.html|title=FILM FEST EKAGRA BEGINS AT BHARAT BHAVAN|date=12 October 2017|work=Dailypioneer|access-date=11 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109191459/http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/bhopal/film-fest-ekagra-begins-at-bhara-bhavan.html|archive-date=9 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It has an art gallery, an open-air amphitheatre facing the Upper Lake, two other theatres and a tribal museum. The Bharat Bhavan as well as the [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly|MP Legislative Assembly]] were designed by Charles Correa.\n\n==Economy==\nThe major industries in the old city are electrical goods, medicinal, cotton, chemicals and jewellery. Other industries include cotton and flour milling, cloth weaving and painting, as well as making matches, sealing wax, and sporting equipment.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9079067/Bhopal#84367.hook| title = Bhopal industries| accessdate = 10 April 2007| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080426030603/http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9079067/Bhopal#84367.hook| archive-date = 26 April 2008| url-status = live| df = dmy-all}}</ref> The residents of Bhopal also engage in large retail businesses. Handicrafts, like [[zardozi]] and ''batua'' (a small string purse, usually used with Indian traditional dresses) are some of the products of the Old City.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.craftandartisans.com/zari-zardozi-tinsel-embroidery.html| title = Zari and Batua| accessdate = 12 April 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070406171714/http://craftandartisans.com/zari-zardozi-tinsel-embroidery.html| archivedate= 6 April 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nBhopal is also home to the [[D B Corp Ltd.|DB Corp]], informally called the Bhaskar Group (named after its major publication ''[[Dainik Bhaskar]]''), a \u20b917&nbsp;billion business conglomerate with a strong presence in media. Its head office is located in Maharana Pratap Nagar.\n\n[[Manjul Publishing House Pvt. Ltd.|Manjul Publishing House]], located in the old city, is a major publishing house made famous by the translation of the [[Harry Potter]] series of novels into [[Hindi]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Kumar Shakti Shekhar|title=Chamber of Secrets translated into Hindi|url=http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/story.aspx?id=NEWEN20050010198|website=NDTV|accessdate=30 October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205051528/http://www.ndtv.com/convergence/ndtv/story.aspx?id=NEWEN20050010198|archivedate=5 December 2008|location=Bhopal|date=10 July 2005}}</ref>\n\n===Industries===\n*[[Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited]], the largest engineering and manufacturing enterprise in India, has a [https://web.archive.org/web/20161030092633/https://www.bhelbpl.co.in/bplweb_new/ unit] in Bhopal. It occupies a large area in the Eastern Part of the city and maintains a suburb named after it. A majority of the residents of the BHEL Suburb are employed by the unit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhelbhopal.com/overview.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120831011035/http://www.bhelbhopal.com/overview.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=31 August 2012|title=Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited, Bhopal|work=bhelbhopal.com}}</ref>\n*[[Mandideep]] is an [[industrial suburb]] of Bhopal. It is located to the south of the city on the [[National Highway 12 (India)|NH 12]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mandideep.com/mg_intro.aspx|title=Association of Industries \u2013 MANDIDEEP|work=mandideep.com|access-date=16 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228101357/http://www.mandideep.com/mg_intro.aspx|archive-date=28 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Mandideep's total exports are worth some 2,300 crore rupees ($500m; \u00a3300m) per year, making it the largest industrial area in Madhya Pradesh. The town is home to Hindustan Electo Graphite (HEG), owning the largest graphite electrode plant in the world and is the largest industrial company in the entire state. Hindustan Electro Graphite (HEG) and Lupin Laboratories ltd. are the dominant companies in the suburb, each exports worth around 900 crore rupees.<ref>{{cite news | last = Madslien | first = Jorn | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/8388167.stm | title = Industrial success fails to lift Bhopal |work=BBC News |date=2 December 2009 | accessdate = 26 July 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100610122326/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/8388167.stm| archivedate= 10 June 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Civic administration==\n[[File:Shivaji statue Bhopal.jpg|thumb|upright|Shivaji statue at Shivaji Nagar Square Bhopal]]\n[[Bhopal Municipal Corporation]] (BMC) is the urban civic body which oversees the needs of Bhopal city. The municipal corporation is spread over an area of {{Convert|285.88|km2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=census /> and the city is divided into 85 wards. Each ward elects a councillor. The winning party elects a council of members, who are responsible for various departments. Madhya Pradesh is one of the few states in India, which uses the Mayor-in-Council (MIC) system and hence the elected representatives of the Bhopal Municipal Corporation are also organised as MIC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.janaagraha.org/asics/report/Madhya-Pradesh-Municipal-Corporation-Act-1956.pdf|title=Madhya Pradesh Municipal Corporation Act 1956|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> There are multiple municipal departments in BMC such as Health and Envrironment; Education, Social JusticeFood and Culture; Planning and Rehabilitation; Public Relations and Library; Fire Brigade and Transport; Power; Engineering; Revenue and Project; Accounting; JnNURM; M.P.U.S.P and General Administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bhopalmunicipal.com/|title=Home|website=Bhopal Municipal Corporation|language=en|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nBhopal Municipal Corporation was ranked 3rd out of 21 Cities for best governance and administrative practices in India in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bhopalmunicipal.com/|title=Home \u2013 Bhopal Municipal Corporation|accessdate=25 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202060148/http://bhopalmunicipal.com/|archive-date=2 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> It scored 3.7 on 10 compared to the national average of 3.3.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nair|first1=Ajesh|title=Annual Survey of India's City-Systems|url=http://janaagraha.org/asics/images/Annual-Survey-of-Indias-City-Systems-2014.pdf|publisher=Janaagraha Centre for Citizenship and Democracy|accessdate=6 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319003215/http://janaagraha.org/asics/images/Annual-Survey-of-Indias-City-Systems-2014.pdf|archive-date=19 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, it was announced that India's first e-waste clinic was being set up in Bhopal. BMC along with Central Pollution Control Board came together to establish this clinic which will enable segregation, processing and disposal of waste, both residential and commercial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/indias-first-e-waste-clinic-to-be-set-up-in-bhopal/article29598165.ece|title=India's first e-waste clinic to be set up in Bhopal|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=4 October 2019|work=The Hindu|access-date=29 January 2020|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> In January 2020, the clinic was inaugurated for operations. It started initially as a three month pilot and if the pilot is successful, the clinics will be opened in other places as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsonair.com/News?title=India%26%2339%3Bs-first-e-waste-clinic-opens-in-Bhopal&id=379236|title=First e-waste clinic opens in Bhopal|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe present [[mayor]] of the city is Alok Sharma.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bhopal Mayor|url=http://www.bhopalmunicipal.com/corporation/bhopal-mayor.html|website=Bhopal Municipal Corporation|accessdate=31 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151031072037/http://www.bhopalmunicipal.com/corporation/bhopal-mayor.html|archive-date=31 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> B Vijay Dutta is the [[municipal commissioner]] of the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bhopalmunicipal.com/corporation/telephone-directory.html|title=Telephones|website=Bhopal Municipal Corporation|language=en|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government and politics==\nBhopal houses the State Legislative Assembly, or the ''[[Madhya Pradesh Vidhan Sabha|Vidhan Sabha]]'', which seats 230 members of Legislative Assembly. The fourteenth (and current) Vidhan Sabha was elected in December 2018.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://mpvidhansabha.nic.in:80/index.aspx | title = Madhya Pradesh Vidhan Sabha| accessdate = 8 March 2007| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170508152326/http://mpvidhansabha.nic.in:80/index.aspx | archivedate = 8 May 2017| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> {{As of|March 2020}}, the party in the majority in Vidhan Sabha is [[Bhartiya Janata Party]] (BJP) with 107 seats which is led by [[Shivraj Singh Chouhan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=How the numbers stack up against Kamal Nath govt ahead of Madhya Pradesh floor test |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/how-the-numbers-stack-up-against-kamal-nath-govt-ahead-of-madhya-pradesh-floor-test-1657753-2020-03-20 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=India Today |date=20 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Bhopal district elects seven seats to the Assembly.\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Bhopal Cycle share.jpg|thumb|right|Bhopal Share Cycles]]\n\n===Air===\n[[File:Raja Bhoj International Airport (BHO) Bhopal India.jpg|thumb|[[Raja Bhoj International Airport]]]]\n{{Main|Bhopal Airport}}\nThe [[Raja Bhoj International Airport]] is located near the suburb of Bairagad and is the primary airport serving the state of Madhya Pradesh, India.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.zeenews.com/news418383.html | title = Indore, Bhopal to have international connectivity soon | publisher = ZeeNews.com | date = 15 January 2008 | accessdate = 19 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThere are three routes or ways to reach the airport: (1) Via Bairagad, (2) Via Panchvati, (3) Via Gandhi Nagar road (N.H 12). From within the city, VIP Road, a four lane road takes one to the airport, which lies 15&nbsp;km to the north of the city. International flights began operations in 2010.\nDomestic direct flight services are operated by Alliance Air, Air India, Spice Jet and Indigo. As of January 2020, Bhopal has non-stop flights to New Delhi, Mumbai, Surat, Jaipur, Ahmedabad, Udaipur, Bangalore, Hyderabad, Pune and Raipur.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.timesnownews.com/business-economy/companies/article/indigo-to-start-non-stop-daily-flight-between-bhopal-hyderabad-and-jabalpur-hyderabad-soon/323025 | title = IndiGo to start non-stop daily flight between Bhopal-Hyderabad and Jabalpur-Hyderabad soon | publisher = timesnownews.com | date = 29 November 2018 | accessdate = 2 December 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181203055506/https://www.timesnownews.com/business-economy/companies/article/indigo-to-start-non-stop-daily-flight-between-bhopal-hyderabad-and-jabalpur-hyderabad-soon/323025 | archive-date = 3 December 2018 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\nThere is only one seasonal international flight from Bhopal and that is to Jeddah, Saudi Arabia and is used mainly by Hajj pilgrims.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/air-india-to-run-flights-from-bhopal-to-pune-hyderabad/1/664838.html | title = Air India to run flights from Bhopal to Pune, Hyderabad | publisher = indiatoday.intoday.com | date = 10 May 2016 | accessdate = 20 July 2016 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160818111544/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/air-india-to-run-flights-from-bhopal-to-pune-hyderabad/1/664838.html | archive-date = 18 August 2016 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Rail===\n[[File:Habibgunj Railway Station-PANOROMA.jpg|thumb|[[Habibganj railway station|Bhopal Habibganj]] station]]\nBhopal lies in the [[West Central Railway Zone (India)|West Central Railway Zone]]. Considering both North-South and East-West train routes, it is one of the most rail connected cities in India which halts more than 200 daily trains, with a total of more than 380 trains within a week. The main stations of Bhopal are the [[Bhopal Junction]] station located in old Bhopal as well as {{rws|Bhopal Habibganj}} station located in new Bhopal. Both of the stations are equipped with WiFi, has enough waiting halls, refreshment center, passenger ticket counter and ticket vending machines, vehicle parking, communication facility, sanitary facility and dedicated government railway police force to ensure security. Altogether the city has six railway stations within its city limits.\n\nThe [[Bhopal Junction]] station as well as {{rws|Bhopal Habibganj}} station are selected along with 47 other railway stations to emerge as The World Class Railway Station. While the work has already started on development of {{rws|Bhopal Habibganj}} as the first world class railway station of India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/india-will-soon-have-world-class-railway-stations-railway-ministry/1/703264.html|title=India will soon have world class railway stations: Railway Ministry|accessdate=25 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221035807/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/india-will-soon-have-world-class-railway-stations-railway-ministry/1/703264.html|archive-date=21 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Bhopal Junction]] and [[Bhopal Habibganj]] have already received ISO 9001:2000 certificate.\n\nThe Bhopal Junction station houses the Divisional Railway Manager's (DRM) head office under West Central railways.\n\n===Roads===\n[[File:Road in Bhopal.jpg|thumb|Bhopal VIP road]]\nNational Highway 46 forms a ring-road around Bhopal which connects it to [[Jabalpur]] in the East (via NH 45). NH 146, a branch of NH 46, connects the city to Sagar in the East. State Highway 18 connects the city with [[Indore]] (with [[Sehore]] and [[Dewas]] on the way). State Highway 23 connects the city to [[Guna, India|Guna]] and [[Berasia]] in the north.\n\n[[File:Kushabhau Thakre ISBT Bhopal (2).jpg|thumb|left|Kushabhau Thakre ISBT Bhopal]]\nAn [[Inter State Bus Terminals|interstate bus terminus]] inaugurated in 2011, the [[Kushabhau Thakre Inter State Bus Terminal]] is located near the Habibganj railway station,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.centralchronicle.com/20060110/1001027.htm | title = Interstare Bus Terminus | accessdate = 16 March 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070526003803/http://www.centralchronicle.com/20060110/1001027.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 26 May 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://dailypioneer.com/state-editions/bhopal/3018-isbt-starts-services-passengers-face-inconvenience.html | title = ISBT starts services, passengers face inconvenience | newspaper = Daily Pioneer | date = 2 September 2011 | accessdate = 16 April 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120423181211/http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/bhopal/3018-isbt-starts-services-passengers-face-inconvenience.html | archive-date = 23 April 2012 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Urban transport ===\n\n==== Bhopal BRTS ====\nThe [[Bhopal BRTS|Bus Rapid Transit System]], which opened in 2013, is run by Bhopal City Link Limited (BCLL). The company has identified 4 trunk and 8 standard routes in the city on which 225 buses would be operated daily (365 a day in a year), from 5 a.m. to 11 p.m. 82 bus stops are built along the 24&nbsp;km long corridor.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.zeenews.com/news615069.html | title = BRTS in Bhopal to be completed by Feb 2011, says Gaur | publisher = ZeeNews.com | date = 30 March 2010 | accessdate = 26 July 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100713190041/http://www.zeenews.com/news615069.html| archivedate= 13 July 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==== Metro Rail ====\nThe [[Bhopal Metro|Bhoj Metro]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/industry/infrastructure/bhopal-metro-to-be-named-after-raja-bhoj-announces-kamal-nath-1569511530540.html|title=Bhopal Metro to be named after Raja Bhoj, announces Kamal Nath|date=26 September 2019|website=Mint|language=en|access-date=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ndtv.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/bhopal-news/bhopal-metro-to-be-bhoj-metro-after-raja-bhoj-kamal-nath-2107765|title=Bhopal Metro To Be Called \"Bhoj Metro\" After Indian King \"Raja Bhoj\": Kamal Nath|website=NDTV.com|access-date=9 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ndtv.com\"/> project is under construction for the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/uncategorized/bhopal-indore-to-have-metro-rail-soon_100145920.html|title=Bhopal, Indore to have Metro Rail soon|work=Thaindian News|access-date=5 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305082637/http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/uncategorized/bhopal-indore-to-have-metro-rail-soon_100145920.html|archive-date=5 March 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n{{See also|List of educational institutions in Bhopal}}\n\n=== Basic education ===\n[[File:NLIUGyanmandir3.JPG|thumb|National Law Institute University]]\nBhopal has more than 550 state-sponsored schools, most of which are affiliated to the [[Madhya Pradesh Board of Secondary Education]] (MPBSE). In addition, there are three [[Kendriya Vidyalaya]]s in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kvsangathan.nic.in/about-kvs/directories/kvs-directory?shs_term_node_tid_depth=178&field_kv_directory_tid=&field_state_directory_tid=2107|title=KVS Directory {{!}} Kendriya Vidyalaya Sanghatan, Government of India|website=Kendriya Vidyalaya Sanghatan {{!}} Government of India|publisher=[[Government of India]]|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref> The city is also served by numerous other private schools affiliated to either CBSE, [[Indian Certificate of Secondary Education|ICSE]], [[Board of Secondary Education, Madhya Pradesh|MPBSE]], [[National Institute of Open Schooling|NIOS]] and [[Cambridge International Examinations|CIE]] (Cambridge).\n\nSchools include [[Delhi Public School, Bhopal]] (CBSE), [[The Sanskaar Valley School]] (ICSE & [[Cambridge International Examinations]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sanskaarvalley.org/sanskaar-affiliations.php|title=Best ICSE School in India, Top 10 ICSE schools in India|website=sanskaarvalley.org|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref> [[Campion School Bhopal|Campion School]] (CBSE), and [[St. Joseph's Convent School, Bhopal|St. Joseph's Convent]] (CBSE).\n\n===Higher education===\n[[File:IIFM arc.jpg|thumb|IIFM arc]]\n\nThere are many universities in Bhopal and its fifteen Institutions of National Importance is the highest number of any town in India outside [[New Delhi]]{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}. The institutes and universities headquartered in the city include:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 93%\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"443\"|Institute\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"145\"|Founded\n|-\n|[[Gandhi Medical College, Bhopal|Gandhi Medical College]]\n|1955\n|-\n| [[Maulana Azad National Institute of Technology]] ||1960\n|-\n| [[Barkatullah University]] ||1970\n|-\n|[[Indian Institute of Forest Management]]||1982\n|-\n| [[Madhya Pradesh Bhoj Open University]] ||1991\n|-\n| [[National Law Institute University]] ||1997\n|-\n| [[Rajiv Gandhi Proudyogiki Vishwavidyalaya]] ||1998\n|-\n| [[Makhanlal Chaturvedi National University of Journalism and Communication]] ||1990\n|-\n|[[National Judicial Academy (India)|National Judicial Academy]] || 1993\n|-\n| [[Indian Institute of Science Education and Research, Bhopal]] ||2008\n|-\n| [[National Institute of Fashion Technology]] || 2008\n|-\n| [[School of Planning and Architecture, Bhopal|School Of Planning And Architecture]] || 2008\n|-\n| [[All India Institute of Medical Sciences, Bhopal|All India Institute of Medical Science]] || 2012\n|-\n|[[Jagran Lakecity University]]\n|2013\n|-\n|[[Indian Institute of Information Technology, Bhopal|Indian Institute of Information Technology]]\n|2017\n|-\n|[[RKDF University]]\n|2012\n|-\n|[[Rabindranath Tagore University]]\n|2010\n|}\n\n== Sports ==\n\n=== Teams ===\n[[Bhopal Badshahs]] is a [[hockey]] team based in Bhopal that plays in World Series Hockey. The team is captained by Indian hockey player [[Sameer Dad]] and coached by [[Vasudevan Bhaskaran]] who was the captain of India's Olympic victory in [[1980 Summer Olympics]] in [[Moscow]]. Badshahs defeated [[Chandigarh Comets]] in the inaugural match of [[2012 World Series Hockey]] 4-3. [[Aishbagh Stadium]] in Bhopal is the home ground of [[Bhopal Badshahs]].\n\n=== Stadiums ===\n* [[Aishbagh Stadium]] is a [[field hockey]] [[stadium]] in Bhopal.\n* [[TT Nagar Stadium]] is a multi-purpose stadium is Bhopal.\n\n== Places of interest ==\n\n=== Nature ===\n[[File:2 elephants man riding one pre historic Bhimbetka rock cave paintings Madhya Pradesh India.jpg|thumb|Bhimbetka pre-historic rock cave painting near Bhopal include 500 sandstone caves and shelters. These are dated to range from 12,000 years ago to [[chalcolithic]] era of human history. They are a [[UNESCO]] World Heritage site.<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/925 Rock Shelters of Bhimbetka] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070308082739/https://whc.unesco.org/pg.cfm?cid=31&id_site=925 |date=8 March 2007 }} UNESCO</ref>]]\n\n[[Bhimbetka rock shelters|Bhimbetka Caves]] are about 35 kilometres from Bhopal city. They have evidence of dwellings of pre-historic man during the Paleolithic era. Rock paintings in the caves are specimens of pre-historic settlements in India. There are about 600 caves, but only 12 are open for visitors. The caves are located in the midst of [[Shorea robusta|sal]] and [[teak]] forests and includes a short trail around the caves. They were discovered by Wakankar in 1957. UNESCO declared Bhimbetka Caves as a World Heritage Site in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/925|title=Rock Shelters of Bhimbetka|publisher=World Heritage Site|accessdate=15 February 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070308082739/https://whc.unesco.org/pg.cfm?cid=31&id_site=925| archivedate= 8 March 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n[[Van Vihar National Park]] is a national park in central India. It is located in Bhopal, the capital city of Madhya Pradesh. Declared a national park in 1979, it covers an area of about 4.45 km2. Although it has the status of a national park, Van Vihar is developed and managed as a modern zoological park, following the guidelines of the Central Zoo Authority. The animals are kept in their near natural habitat. Most of the animals are either orphaned brought from various parts of the state or those, which are exchanged from other zoos. No animal is deliberately captured from the forest.[1] Van Vihar is unique because it allows easy access to the visitors through a road passing through the park, security of animals assured from poachers by building trenches and walls, chain-link fence and by providing natural habitat to the animals.\n\n=== Activity centres ===\nThe [[Indira Gandhi Rashtriya Manav Sangrahalaya|Museum of Mankind]] in Bhopal exhibits tribal and folk houses from all corners of India.<ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/museum-of-mankind-bhopal-relocates-tribal-houses-across-india/1/155488.html A House of Tribal Tradition- Bhopal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150509012955/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/museum-of-mankind-bhopal-relocates-tribal-houses-across-india/1/155488.html |date=9 May 2015 }} India Today</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==People from Bhopal==\n\n=== Politics, Civil Service, Science ===\n\n*[[Shankar Dayal Sharma]] \u2013 9th [[President of India]]\n*[[Najma Heptulla]] \u2013 Union Minister\n*[[Raghuram Rajan]] \u2013 23rd Governor Of RBI\n*[[Kailash Chandra Joshi]] \u2013 Former Chief Minister of Madhya Pradesh\n*[[Abdul Hafiz Mohamed Barakatullah]] \u2013 Revolutionary\n*[[Munshi Hakimuddin]] - Chief Secretary at [[Bhopal state]], known for [[Sadr Diwani Adalat]]\n*[[Anees Ahmed]] \u2013 Lawyer in United Nations Peacekeeping Operations and United Nations International Criminal Tribunals\n*[[Abdul Qadeer Khan]] \u2013 Pakistani nuclear physicist\n\n=== Literature ===\n\n*[[Javed Akhtar]] \u2013 poet, screenwriter and lyricist\n*[[Asad Bhopali]] \u2013 poet and lyricist\n*[[Kaif Bhopali]] \u2013 poet and lyricist\n*[[Manzar Bhopali]] \u2013 poet\n*[[Manzoor Ahtesham]] \u2013 writer\n*[[Bashir Badr]] \u2013 poet\n\n=== Sports ===\n\n* [[Aslam Sher Khan]] \u2013 National hockey player and Member of Parliament\n* [[Mansoor Ali Khan Pataudi]] \u2013 Former Captain of the [[India national cricket team]]\n* [[Sameer Dad]] \u2013 National hockey player\n*[[Jalaluddin Rizvi]] \u2013 National hockey player and [[Arjuna Award]] winner\n* [[Shahryar Khan]] \u2013 Chairman of [[Pakistan Cricket Board]]\n\n=== Film and television ===\n*[[Divyanka Tripathi]] \u2013 Actress\n*[[Vipul Roy]] \u2013 Actor\n*[[Eisha Singh]] \u2013 Actress\n*[[Arshi Khan]] \u2013 Actress, model\n*[[Shawar Ali]] \u2013 Actor\n*[[Sara Khan (TV actress)]]\n*[[Annu Kapoor]] \u2013 Actor, TV presenter and National Film Award winner\n*[[Shoaib Ibrahim]] \u2013 TV Actor\n*[[Jaya Bachchan]] \u2013 Actress\n*[[Saumya Tandon]] \u2013 Television actress\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Bhopal (Lok Sabha constituency)]]\n*[[Regional Museum of Natural History, Bhopal]]\n*[[Bhabha Engineering Research Institute]]\n*[[Sagar Institute of Science and Technology]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Sinha\n  | first = Indra\n  | title = Animal's People\n  | publisher = Simon & Schuster\n  | year = 2007\n  | isbn = 978-1-4165-7878-9\n  | ref = harv\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/animalspeople00sinh\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Lapierre\n  | first = Dominique\n  | title = Five Past Midnight in Bhopal\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/fivepastmidnight00domi\n  | url-access = registration\n  | publisher = Warner Books\n  | year = 2002\n  | isbn = 0-7432-2035-8\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Khan\n  | first = Shaharyar\n  | title = Begums of Bhopal, A Dynasty of Women Rulers in Raj India\n  | edit